<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08071k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08071k">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08071k"> 71(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> afore me</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The Puritans caused a law to be enacted in 1606 by which profane language was prohibited on the stage (3 James I. chap. 21), and consequently words like <i>&apos;zounds</i> were changed or omitted in Shakespearian plays, &hellip; <i>&apos;fore me</i> (<i>afore me</i>) or <i>trust me</i> <font color="green">[was substituted]</font> for (<i>a</i>)<i>fore God</i>; <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJGS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#OJGS"><cite title="source">The Growth and Structure of the English Language</cite></a>, 4th ed. (Jul 1923) 237</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
